7, 8. mobilium (ps) equals ‘though fickle, they yet give him all three offices,² tergeminis (ps). But the order &nobilium turba Quiritium is frequent (see P. 19 and 20a); and so is the grouping tergeminis tollere honoribus (see P. 21).

9. proprio (ps) i.e. all his own, not shared in partnership nor owned bv the government. Compare privatis Odes 2. 15. 15, meis Odes 3. 16. 27, Epod. 1. 26, and suis Epod. 2. 3. But see too P. 21.

10. Libycis (ps): the corn comes, not from his own estate, but from Afm‘ca; also see P. 21.

11. patrios (ps): this man delights in his ancestral farm, however small. Contrast Libycz's...a7‘ez's of l. 10, and see on proprio l. 9 above.

12. Attalicis (p): the generic adjective is often, as one would expect, pre- positive. See P. 37.

14. Myrtoum: perhaps the worst sea in the Mediterranean (cp. Odes 4. 5. 9, 10), off Cape Malia, enough to frighten an experienced sailor‚ much more a novice. One need not be a confirmed believer in Porphyrion's speciem pro genere ponit. See on Odes 1. 35. 7.

For the two adjectives Myrtoum pavidus followed by the two nouns in chiastic order see P. 10, and for the collocation of the adjectives see Odes 1. 5. 9.

mare: single word after the verb, as so often in Livy.

15. Icariis (p) : again the sea is the dangerous Aegean. See too P. 10.
